</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="800" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[132,776,1046,2030]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">
The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[252,346,1046,1072]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[252,346,1046,1072]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises medium to large-sized bears from the late Miocene, with an omnivorous diet (
<bibRefCitation author="MONTOYA P. &amp; ALCALA L. &amp; MORALES J." pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="123 - 151" refId="ref8674" refString="MONTOYA P., ALCALA L. &amp; MORALES J. 2001. - Indarctos (Ursidae, Mammalia) from the Spanish Turolian (Upper Miocene). Scripta Geologica 122: 123 - 151." type="journal article" year="2001">
Montoya 
<emphasis box="[132,185,1110,1136]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="VIRANTA S." box="[263,407,1110,1136]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="325 - 327" refId="ref9733" refString="VIRANTA S. 2004. - Habitat preferences of European Middle Miocene omnivorous ursids. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica 49: 325 - 327." type="journal article" year="2004">Viranta 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="ABELLA J." box="[431,561,1110,1136]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" refId="ref6795" refString="ABELLA J. 2011. - Indarctos arctoides Deperet, 1895 (Carnivora, Mammalia) del yacimiento vallesiense de Batallones 3 (cuenca de Madrid) [Indarctos arctoides Deperet, 1895 (Carnivora, Mammalia) from the vallesian locality of Batallones 3 (Madrid Basin)]. PhD dissertation, unpublished. Madrid: Universidad Autonoma de Madrid- Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales (CSIC) (in Spanish)." type="book" year="2011">Abella 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="ABELLA J. &amp; VALENCIANO A. &amp; RAMOS A. &amp; MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J." box="[577,767,1110,1136]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="77711" refId="ref6944" refString="ABELLA J., VALENCIANO A., PEREZ- RAMOS A., MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J. 2013. - On the socio-sexual behaviour of the extinct ursid Indarctos arctoides: An approach based on its baculum size and morphology. PLoS ONE 8: e 77711. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0073711" type="journal article" year="2013">
Abella 
<emphasis box="[652,704,1110,1136]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="MONESCILLO M. F. G. &amp; SALESA M. J. &amp; ANTON M. &amp; SILICEO G. &amp; MORALES J." box="[132,363,1142,1168]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="699 - 709" refId="ref8544" refString="MONESCILLO M. F. G., SALESA M. J., ANTON M., SILICEO G. &amp; MORALES J. 2014. - Machairodus aphanistus (Felidae, Machairodontinae, Homotherini) from the Late Miocene (Vallesian, MN 10) site of Batallones- 3 (Torrejon de Velasco, Madrid, Spain). Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 34: 699 - 709. https: // doi. org / 1 0.1080 / 02724634.2013.804415" type="journal article" year="2014">
Monescillo 
<emphasis box="[254,303,1142,1168]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="DOMINGO M. S. &amp; DOMINGO L. &amp; ABELLA J. &amp; VALENCIANO A. &amp; BADGLEY C. &amp; MORALES J." box="[375,593,1142,1168]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="489 - 507" refId="ref7948" refString="DOMINGO M. S., DOMINGO L., ABELLA J., VALENCIANO A., BADGLEY C. &amp; MORALES J. 2016. - Feeding ecology and habitat preferences of top predators from two Miocene carnivore-rich assemblages. Paleobiology 42: 489 - 507. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / pab. 2015.50" type="journal article" year="2016">
Domingo 
<emphasis box="[484,533,1142,1168]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). Although comprehensively studied, there is not a full consensus about their phylogenetic relationships. Some authors (
<bibRefCitation author="HENDEY Q. B." box="[575,719,1206,1232]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="115 - 132" refId="ref8256" refString="HENDEY Q. B. 1972. - A Pliocene ursid from South Africa. Annals of the South African Museum 59: 115 - 132. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 40938928" type="journal article" year="1972">Hendey 1972</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="QIU Z. - X. &amp; DENG T. &amp; WANG B. - Y." pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="265 - 302" refId="ref9145" refString="QIU Z. - X., DENG T. &amp; WANG B. - Y. 2014. - A Late Miocene Ursavus skull from Guanghe, Gansu, China. Vertebrata PalAsiatica 52: 265 - 302." type="journal article" year="2014">
Qiu 
<emphasis box="[132,182,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
) relate them to the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Wagner" authorityYear="1837" box="[512,647,1238,1264]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Agriotherium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[512,647,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Agriotherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(considered a 
<taxonomicName box="[149,303,1269,1295]" class="Mammalia" family="Hemicyonidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Hemicyonidae</taxonomicName>
by the authors of the present paper) and others consider it to be a basal 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fischer von Waldheim" authorityYear="1817" box="[415,495,1301,1327]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Ursidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="ABELLA J. &amp; ALBA D. V. &amp; ROBLES J. M. &amp; VALENCIANO A. &amp; ROTGERS C. &amp; CARMONA R. &amp; MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J." box="[510,692,1301,1328]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="48985" refId="ref6870" refString="ABELLA J., ALBA D. V., ROBLES J. M., VALENCIANO A., ROTGERS C., CARMONA R., MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J. 2012. - Kretzoiarctos gen. nov., the oldest member of the giant panda clade. PLoS ONE 7: e 48985. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0048985" type="journal article" year="2012">
Abella 
<emphasis box="[582,631,1301,1327]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="ABELLA J. &amp; MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J." box="[704,759,1302,1328]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="11 - 18" refId="ref7009" refString="ABELLA J., MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J. 2014. - Paleodiversity of the Superfamily Ursoidea (Carnivora, Mammalia) in the Spanish Neogene, related to environmental changes. Journal of Iberian Geology 40: 11 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.5209 / rev _ JIGE. 2014. v 40. n 1.44083" type="journal article" year="2014">2014</bibRefCitation>
). However, the most recent phylogenetic analyses, based on cranial, mandibular and dental characters, include 
<taxonomicName box="[571,662,1365,1391]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[571,662,1365,1391]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Greve" authorityYear="1894" box="[132,283,1397,1423]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ailuropodinae">Ailuropodinae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="ABELLA J. &amp; ALBA D. V. &amp; ROBLES J. M. &amp; VALENCIANO A. &amp; ROTGERS C. &amp; CARMONA R. &amp; MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J." box="[297,476,1397,1423]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="48985" refId="ref6870" refString="ABELLA J., ALBA D. V., ROBLES J. M., VALENCIANO A., ROTGERS C., CARMONA R., MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J. 2012. - Kretzoiarctos gen. nov., the oldest member of the giant panda clade. PLoS ONE 7: e 48985. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0048985" type="journal article" year="2012">
Abella 
<emphasis box="[368,417,1397,1423]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="QIU Z. - X. &amp; DENG T. &amp; WANG B. - Y." box="[488,644,1397,1423]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="265 - 302" refId="ref9145" refString="QIU Z. - X., DENG T. &amp; WANG B. - Y. 2014. - A Late Miocene Ursavus skull from Guanghe, Gansu, China. Vertebrata PalAsiatica 52: 265 - 302." type="journal article" year="2014">
Qiu 
<emphasis box="[536,584,1397,1423]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). This genus was indeed the predominant bear taxon during most of the late Miocene in the Northern Hemisphere (
<bibRefCitation author="ABELLA J. &amp; MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J." box="[550,733,1461,1487]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="11 - 18" refId="ref7009" refString="ABELLA J., MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J. 2014. - Paleodiversity of the Superfamily Ursoidea (Carnivora, Mammalia) in the Spanish Neogene, related to environmental changes. Journal of Iberian Geology 40: 11 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.5209 / rev _ JIGE. 2014. v 40. n 1.44083" type="journal article" year="2014">
Abella 
<emphasis box="[622,672,1461,1487]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[132,776,1046,2030]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">
The first specimen currently referred to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[681,775,1493,1519]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[681,775,1493,1519]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consists of a left mandible fragment from the Greek locality of Pikermi identified as 
<emphasis box="[359,484,1557,1582]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Hyaenarctos</emphasis>
sp. by 
<bibRefCitation author="DAMES W." box="[558,714,1557,1583]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="132 - 139" refId="ref7858" refString="DAMES W. 1883. - Uber das Vorkommen von Hyaenarctos in den Pliocan-Ablagerungen von Pikermi bei Athen. Sitzungsberichte der Gesellschaft Naturforschender Freunde zu Berlin 1883 (8): 132 - 139. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 8789424" type="journal article" year="1883">Dames (1883)</bibRefCitation>
, with 
<bibRefCitation author="WEITHOFER A." box="[132,321,1588,1615]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="225 - 292" refId="ref9807" refString="WEITHOFER A. 1888. - Beitrage zur Kenntniss der Fauna von Pikermi bei Athen. Beitrage zur Palantologie und Geologie Osterreich-Ungarns und des Orients 6: 225 - 292." type="journal article" year="1888">Weithofer (1888)</bibRefCitation>
later referring it to 
<emphasis box="[530,631,1589,1614]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">H. atticus</emphasis>
. However, in 1884 Lydekker created the species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lydekker" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[509,672,1620,1646]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punjabiensis">
<emphasis box="[509,672,1620,1646]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">H. punjabiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a broken maxilla (which included P4-M1) from the Siwaliks in 
<collectingCountry box="[160,220,1684,1710]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">India</collectingCountry>
. In that paper he also assigned a maxilla with P4-M2 and a skull with Upper canine and P4-M2 from other localities to the same genus. The latter specimen has been the cause of most of the later taxonomic confusion in comparisons among species since this skull clearly can be assigned to the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Wagner" authorityYear="1837" box="[132,270,1843,1869]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Agriotherium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[132,270,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Agriotherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to the lack of a clear talon and different relative development of the main cusps in the M2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[132,776,1046,2030]" lastBlockId="5.[813,1456,217,1392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">
<bibRefCitation author="PILGRIM G. E." box="[155,323,1907,1934]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="264 - 326" refId="ref9065" refString="PILGRIM G. E. 1913. - The correlation of the Siwaliks with the Mammal Horizons of Europe. Records of the Geological Survey of India 43: 264 - 326." type="journal article" year="1913">Pilgrim (1913)</bibRefCitation>
moved some of these remains from the junior synonym genus 
<emphasis box="[390,517,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Hyaenarctos</emphasis>
(also later synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Wagner" authorityYear="1837" box="[132,270,1971,1997]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Agriotherium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[132,270,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Agriotherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) to the newly created genus 
<taxonomicName box="[579,673,1971,1997]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[579,673,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on a maxillary fragment with M2 and broken M1 from the Siwa- liks. However, it was not until a year later (
<bibRefCitation author="PILGRIM G. E." box="[1258,1399,217,243]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="264 - 326" refId="ref9065" refString="PILGRIM G. E. 1913. - The correlation of the Siwaliks with the Mammal Horizons of Europe. Records of the Geological Survey of India 43: 264 - 326." type="journal article" year="1913">Pilgrim 1913</bibRefCitation>
) that he measured, figured and compared this specimen to other, similar fossils, describing 
<emphasis box="[1074,1295,281,307]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">
<taxonomicName box="[1074,1165,281,307]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Indarctos</taxonomicName>
salmontanus
</emphasis>
as the 
<typeStatus box="[1363,1408,282,308]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus (
<bibRefCitation author="PILGRIM G. E." box="[1003,1159,313,339]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="225 - 233" refId="ref9098" refString="PILGRIM G. E. 1914. - Further description of Indarctos salmontanus Pilgrim, the new genus of bear from the Middle Siwaliks, with some remarks on the fossil indian Ursidae. Records of the Geological Survey of India 44: 225 - 233." type="journal article" year="1914">Pilgrim, 1914</bibRefCitation>
). Later 
<bibRefCitation author="BARYSHNIKOV G. F." box="[1240,1455,313,339]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="83 - 89" refId="ref7514" refString="BARYSHNIKOV G. F. 2002. - Late Miocene Indarctos punjabiensis atticus (Carnivora, Ursidae) in Ukraine with survey of Indarctos records from the former USSR. Russian Journal of Theriology 1: 83 - 89. https: // doi. org / 10.15298 / rusjtheriol. 01.2.02" type="journal article" year="2002">Baryshnikov (2002)</bibRefCitation>
accepted only two species of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1234,1328,345,371]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1234,1328,345,371]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, literally he stated: “The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1009,1102,376,402]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1009,1102,376,402]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises two species. 
<emphasis box="[1346,1455,376,402]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">I. arctoides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="DEPERET C." box="[820,980,408,435]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="432 - 434" refId="ref7903" refString="DEPERET C. 1895. - Resultats des fouilles paleontologiques dans le Miocene superieur de la colline de Montredon. Comptes rendus hebdomadaires des Seances de l'Academie des Sciences 121: 432 - 434. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 36256646" type="journal article" year="1895">Depéret, 1895</bibRefCitation>
) was found in Europe, northern Africa and 
<collectingCountry box="[813,890,440,466]" name="Turkey" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Turkey</collectingCountry>
, dating as the Vallesian (MN 9-11). 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lydekker, 1884)" baseAuthorityName="Lydekker" baseAuthorityYear="1884" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punjabiensis">
<emphasis box="[1301,1455,440,466]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">I. punjabiensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="LYDEKKER R." box="[819,988,472,498]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="178 - 363" refId="ref8374" refString="LYDEKKER R. 1884. - Indian Tertiary and post-Tertiary Vertebrata. Part 6. Siwalik and Narbada Carnivora. Memoirs of the Geological Survey of India. Palaeontologia Indica 10: 178 - 363. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 53674503" type="journal article" year="1884">Lydekker, 1884</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
known from the Turolian (MN 10-13) had a Holarctic range, occurring in Europe, northern Africa, in the central, southern and eastern parts of Asia, and in North America”. Therefore, although indirectly, he synonymized Pilgrim’s 
<typeStatus box="[911,957,600,626]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">type</typeStatus>
species with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lydekker" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[1100,1328,600,626]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punjabiensis">
<emphasis box="[1100,1328,600,626]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos punjabiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[813,1456,217,1392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">
The oldest record of 
<taxonomicName box="[1038,1126,632,658]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1038,1126,632,658]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises some specimens from MN 
<quantity box="[860,898,664,690]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.286" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" unit="in" value="9.0">9 in</quantity>
the Vallesian basin of Vallès-Penedès, at the localities of Can Porull (
<bibRefCitation author="VILLALTA Y COMELLA J. F. DE &amp; CRUSAFONT PAIRO M." box="[943,1220,695,722]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="45 - 62" refId="ref9600" refString="VILLALTA Y COMELLA J. F. DE &amp; CRUSAFONT PAIRO M. 1943. - Indarctos vireti, nova sp., un nuevo ursido del grupo de los Hemicionidos del Mioceno superior del Valles-Penedes [Indarctos vireti, nova sp., a new ursid of the hemicyonids group from Late Miocene from Valles-Penedes]. Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cientificas 1943: 45 - 62 (in Spanish)." type="journal article" year="1943">Villalta &amp; Crusafont 1943</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="VILLALTA Y COMELLA J. F. DE &amp; CRUSAFONT PAIRO M." box="[1235,1289,696,722]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="81 - 121" refId="ref9673" refString="VILLALTA Y COMELLA J. F. DE &amp; CRUSAFONT PAIRO M. 1948. - Nuevas aportaciones al conocimiento de los carnivoros pontienses del Valles-Penedes [New data to the knowledge of the pontian carnivorans from Valles-Penedes]. Publicaciones del Instituto de Geologia de Barcelona, Miscelanea Almera 7: 81 - 121 (in Spanish)." type="journal article" year="1948">1948</bibRefCitation>
) and later from Can Llobateres (
<bibRefCitation author="CRUSAFONT PAIRO M. &amp; KURTEN B." box="[992,1278,727,754]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="1 - 29" refId="ref7825" refString="CRUSAFONT PAIRO M. &amp; KURTEN B. 1976. - Bears and bear-dogs from the Vallesian of the Valles-Penedes Basin, Spain. Acta Zoologica Fennica 144: 1 - 29." type="journal article" year="1976">Crusafont &amp; Kurtén 1976</bibRefCitation>
). These remains were assigned to 
<taxonomicName authority="Villalta &amp; Crusafont, 1943" authorityName="Villalta &amp; Crusafont" authorityYear="1943" box="[989,1433,759,785]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vireti">
<emphasis box="[989,1139,759,785]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos vireti</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="VILLALTA Y COMELLA J. F. DE &amp; CRUSAFONT PAIRO M." box="[1146,1433,759,785]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="45 - 62" refId="ref9600" refString="VILLALTA Y COMELLA J. F. DE &amp; CRUSAFONT PAIRO M. 1943. - Indarctos vireti, nova sp., un nuevo ursido del grupo de los Hemicionidos del Mioceno superior del Valles-Penedes [Indarctos vireti, nova sp., a new ursid of the hemicyonids group from Late Miocene from Valles-Penedes]. Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cientificas 1943: 45 - 62 (in Spanish)." type="journal article" year="1943">Villalta &amp; Crusafont, 1943</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a small sized member of the genus, with elongated molars, more primitive (less reduced) premolars, and well-developed diastemas between them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="800" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="5.[813,1456,217,1392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">
<taxonomicName authority="(Depéret, 1895)" authorityName="Depéret" authorityYear="1895" box="[835,1217,887,914]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arctoides">
<emphasis box="[835,1028,887,913]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos arctoides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="DEPERET C." box="[1045,1210,887,914]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="432 - 434" refId="ref7903" refString="DEPERET C. 1895. - Resultats des fouilles paleontologiques dans le Miocene superieur de la colline de Montredon. Comptes rendus hebdomadaires des Seances de l'Academie des Sciences 121: 432 - 434. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 36256646" type="journal article" year="1895">Depéret, 1895</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, is documented from MN10. This species was first described from the French locality of Montredon, and can be found along the northern edge of the Mediterranean Sea, including 
<collectingCountry box="[1115,1175,982,1008]" name="Spain" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Spain</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1183,1251,983,1009]" name="France" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">France</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1298,1369,982,1008]" name="Turkey" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="TOBIEN H." pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="7 - 31" refId="ref9306" refString="TOBIEN H. 1955. - Neue und wenig bekannte Carnivoren aus den Unterpliozanen Dinotheriensanden Rheinhessens. Notizblatt des Hessischen L. - Amts fur Bodenforshung zu Wiesbaden 83: 7 - 31." type="journal article" year="1955">Tobien 1955</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="GERAADS D. &amp; KAYA T. &amp; MAYDA S." box="[880,1080,1014,1041]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="523 - 544" refId="ref8144" refString="GERAADS D., KAYA T. &amp; MAYDA S. 2005. - Late Miocene large mammals from Yulafli, Thrace region, Turkey, and their biogeographic implications. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica 50 (3): 523 - 544." type="journal article" year="2005">
Geraads 
<emphasis box="[971,1020,1014,1040]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2005
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="ABELLA J." box="[1093,1219,1014,1041]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" refId="ref6795" refString="ABELLA J. 2011. - Indarctos arctoides Deperet, 1895 (Carnivora, Mammalia) del yacimiento vallesiense de Batallones 3 (cuenca de Madrid) [Indarctos arctoides Deperet, 1895 (Carnivora, Mammalia) from the vallesian locality of Batallones 3 (Madrid Basin)]. PhD dissertation, unpublished. Madrid: Universidad Autonoma de Madrid- Museo Nacional de Ciencias Naturales (CSIC) (in Spanish)." type="book" year="2011">Abella 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="ABELLA J. &amp; MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J." box="[1232,1413,1014,1041]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="11 - 18" refId="ref7009" refString="ABELLA J., MONTOYA P. &amp; MORALES J. 2014. - Paleodiversity of the Superfamily Ursoidea (Carnivora, Mammalia) in the Spanish Neogene, related to environmental changes. Journal of Iberian Geology 40: 11 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.5209 / rev _ JIGE. 2014. v 40. n 1.44083" type="journal article" year="2014">
Abella 
<emphasis box="[1304,1353,1014,1040]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[813,1456,217,1392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">
Finally, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lydekker" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[915,1132,1046,1072]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punjabiensis">
<emphasis box="[915,1132,1046,1072]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos punjabiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(incl. 
<emphasis box="[1195,1280,1047,1072]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">I. atticus</emphasis>
) has an extensive record in the Iberian Peninsula from MN10 to MN12. Most of these specimens were studied in detail by 
<bibRefCitation author="MONTOYA P. &amp; ALCALA L. &amp; MORALES J." box="[1227,1451,1110,1137]" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" pagination="123 - 151" refId="ref8674" refString="MONTOYA P., ALCALA L. &amp; MORALES J. 2001. - Indarctos (Ursidae, Mammalia) from the Spanish Turolian (Upper Miocene). Scripta Geologica 122: 123 - 151." type="journal article" year="2001">
Montoya 
<emphasis box="[1327,1373,1110,1136]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">et al.</emphasis>
(2001)
</bibRefCitation>
. Following the arguments of that paper we accept three species of 
<taxonomicName box="[841,931,1174,1200]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[841,931,1174,1200]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; four, if we take include the peculiar 
<emphasis box="[1325,1454,1174,1200]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">I. anthracites</emphasis>
(Weithofer, 1889), which is thought to be an insular form and is only represented by a single published specimen. These are 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Villalta &amp; Crusafont" authorityYear="1943" box="[813,886,1270,1295]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vireti">
<emphasis box="[813,886,1270,1295]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">I. vireti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[898,1004,1269,1295]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">I. arctoides</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lydekker" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[1054,1197,1269,1295]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="800" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punjabiensis">
<emphasis box="[1054,1197,1269,1295]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">I. punjabiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the last species having the temporal range. The present study increases the stratigraphic range of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1088,1178,1333,1359]" class="Mammalia" family="Ursidae" genus="Indarctos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="5" pageNumber="807" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1088,1178,1333,1359]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="800">Indarctos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Iberian Peninsula to the lower part of MN13.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
